1943 Izhevsk Mosin 91/30 - $200

Great example of a mosin. All matching (not forced match) numbers. Great bore, no corrosion or pitting. Has not been refinished in any way. Metal is in wonderful condition. Comes with sling, 2 ammo pouches, oiler, bayonet, and 4 stripper clips. I have close to 400 rounds that I can sell with it for $.25/rd.

Yugo Capture K98 Mauser - $350

All numbers stamped matching and no import mark that I have been able to find. Has front sight hood, cleaning rod, and capture screws on trigger housing. Rifle is in great shape. These rifles were German production that were captured by the Yugoslavians. Receiver markings were scrubbed off and stamped with the Yugoslavian crest and "PREDUZECE 44" which was the factory that the work was completed. There are still some waffenamps on the components (sight, bolt, firing pin). Mirror bore and incredible shooter. Comes with bayonet, sling, and ammo pouch. 665 rounds of ammo available for $.45/rd.

Take both rifles for $495

title: For Sale:  Spanish Revolver in .32-20
postcontent:
For sale is a Spanish copy of S&W Model 1905 revolvers, produced in Eibar, Spain, in 1924. Beneath the left wooden grip panel is "F" and "A" etched into the frame, suggesting this is a "Francisco Arizmendi" manufacture revolver. The caliber is one popular for the time, but now since relegated to antiques or niche shooters. I am not totally sure of the proof marks, but they seem commensurate with manufacturer, location and time period. 

The gun itself is in good working condition and was in the possession of a friend before being passed to me as payment of a debt. I had the gun inspected by Chris Barnard of Accu-Arms for mechanical issues and to determine if it was safe to shoot, as well as the internals cleaned and worked over. 

Cylinder lockup is solid, and the release mechanism near the forcing cone works perfectly fine. The trigger pull is smooth in both double and single actions, though a strong finger is needed I might think. The barrel has some pitting, but the rifling looks to be in good shape overall. The finish is as is in the photos. 

With this gun comes a box of 50 .32-20 as pictured. 

I am asking $180 for the gun. No low-balling, and the price is generally firm. I am pretty flexible in meeting up with potential buyers in terms of location. However, work pushes meet up times to after 7PM during the week. Weekends are fair game during the day.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson .38 Special
postcontent:
For sale is a Smith and Wesson 3rd Model, 4th Change in .38 SPL, manufactured in 1923.

The gun has a nickel finish and mother of pearl grips. Cylinder lockup is good, and trigger pull is very good, and very smooth and pleasant in both double and single action. There are blemishes to the nickel finish of course, and especially on the cylinder. Slight imperfections to the rifling is present, but the barrel itself is in good condition. Having shot the gun numerous times, it performs very well, if shooting a bit low depending on what load you are using. 

One defect of importance is a slight bulge in the barrel just behind the front sight blade. The bulge is not noticeable unless one feels along the barrel, and does not hinder performance nor represents a danger in shooting the gun. Of some concern when I acquired the gun through some horse trading, I was informed by several collectors that all this does is lower value, and by a gunsmith that there might be a slight loss of accuracy (not that I noticed anyhow). The gunsmith also checked the rest of the internals and cleaned them. 

The 34th Edition of the Blue Book of Gun Values lists the gun at 50% condition as $400, but due to the barrel bulge, I am listing the gun at $275 or best offer. No low-balling or obviously unreasonable prices; any such attempted will simply be deleted. 

Due to the gun's age, character of the standard load at the time, and material used in manufacturing, I must note that it is highly inadvisable to shoot anything more than basic .38 SPL loads through the gun -- no +p or +p+. The gun is an interesting piece in any case, and for being over 90 years old, still functions very well. 

I am generally flexible in traveling to a meeting location within the Missoula area and just outside of it after 7PM on the weekdays. Weekends are generally open. Cash is preferred.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Last call AK bull pup and cash boot
postcontent: I don't know what armslist has come to that I can't make a deal on this rifle. I picked it up to see if I liked a bull pup but it turns out I like the idea more than the application. It's an egyptian maddi with the bull pup conversion. I bought it used so I'm not sure of it's history but through some research I found that these were available as a factory conversion as well as a kit you could install yourself. I'm not sure which this is for certain. maybe if I get a few extra minutes during normal business hours I'll put a call in to CAI and see if I can find out. The exterior has some normal minor wear but the bore and internals are in excellent condition and I don't think it's seen a lot of use. I'm no newbie to the AK world so I have a pretty good idea of what to look for. The rifle comes as pictured and I do have one other option for optics if you don't care for red dots. In my research into these rifles I've had a very difficult time finding others to get a feel for fair pricing. I was only able to find one identical rifle on an auction site and it sold for $1400. Now I'm a fair guy and I know this shows some handling wear, and to be totally honest I don't personally think even a perfect specimen is really worth that, so I'm setting my price at $900 cash or trade. This is a great opportunity for all you guys that have told me you only buy when it's a great deal. If your offering a trade, I'm going to look at my three favorite gun stores and take the best price listed for the make and model of your trade offer, then subtract 20 percent from new cost to arrive at fair used value.(by the way if I used the same equation for my gun value it would be $1120 and mine is no longer available as a factory build and hard to find too so save that line for the next guy too)  Condition will also factor in as well as any extras that you might offer. If you think I'm being unfair please just move on along to the next ad. I've been doing this for a while now and to be honest it's wearing me out, so if you'd want to make a deal please make your best offer up front. I don't have the time or energy to haggle for hours or days and not reach a deal. If you want to play barter king, try it on the next guy. I'll send a polite no thank you then simply stop responding. I am also burnt out on all the traveling to make a deal. I will only meet in or very close to Danville. If your honest and use those manners your mama taught you we'll get along just fine. Lastly as seen in the picture I do have cash to boot if your trade is worth more than my asking price. What's pictured is what I have to work with so asking for more than $500 is just a waste of time, it's all I can spare at the moment. If your still interested after reading all that please feel free to contact me. I'm a pretty easy guy to deal with but the crowd that hangs around armslist has shown me I need to be very clear in my expectations or I get offers that make the pawn stores look generous.

This is a Yugoslavian variant of the AK-47 / AKM, chambered in 7.62x39mm. It has an under-folder stock for greater portability as these types of models were usually issued to paratroopers. The receiver is 1 1/2 times the thickness of any other AK under-folder design from any other former Warsaw Pact nation, leading to an incredibly sturdy received design.

The furniture (Pistol grip, upper and lower hand-guards) has been upgraded to Hogue M70 furniture, which is far and away an improvement over the original furniture it came with. The left strut of the under-folding stock is wound in para cord as it makes for a more comfortable cheek-weld.
The sights are straight and the rifle shoots well and true. In the approximately 200 rounds that went through it I experienced no FTEs or FTFs.
